description: From Latin interclūdō; inter (“between”) + claudō (“to shut”). See close.

verbs.description: interclude (third-person singular simple present intercludes, present participle intercluding, simple past and past participle intercluded)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To shut off or cut off from a place or course, by something intervening; to intercept; to interrupt.
examples: Next morning the combined forces appeared again in order of battle, in front of the Athenian works, and by their position intercluded the communication of the Athenian general with his fort of Labdalum, and with his northern lines.
